          "body": "Verse 15 is the linchpin of the covenant's permanence. 'But My *chesed* shall not depart from him, as I took it away from Saul.' Saul lost the throne because of personal disobedience; the Davidic line will not. The covenant *chesed* — covenant loyalty, steadfast love — is no longer keyed to the king's faithfulness but to God's. This is what makes the Davidic Covenant a covenant of grace and what allows it to survive Solomon's idolatry, Rehoboam's foolishness, Manasseh's atrocities, and ultimately the exile. The throne goes dormant in Babylon but cannot be revoked; the *chesed* endures. The same word will dominate Psalm 89, the canonical meditation on this very chapter, and will reach its fullest manifestation in the Davidic Son who Himself is the embodiment of *chesed* (Luke 1:54-55, 68-79)."
