          "body": "'I will be a father to him, and he will be a son to Me' (v. 14). At one level this describes Solomon — disciplined by 'the rod of men and the strokes of the sons of men' when he commits iniquity (and he will, 1 Kings 11). But the New Testament reads this verse as ultimately about Christ. Hebrews 1:5 quotes it directly as evidence of the Son's supremacy over angels; the same Father-Son language appears at the baptism (Matt 3:17) and transfiguration (Matt 17:5). The discipline-with-the-rod clause cannot apply to the sinless Son in the same way — but at the cross, the rod of men did fall on the Davidic Son, who was 'numbered with the transgressors' (Isa 53:12) and bore iniquity not His own (2 Cor 5:21). The typology runs through Solomon and lands on Christ; the Father-Son covenant relation finds its eternal referent in the eternal Son who sits on David's throne forever (Luke 1:32-33)."
