          "title": "David's response — the model of covenant reception (7:18-29)",
          "body": "The final twelve verses are the most extended prayer in the Davidic narrative and arguably the New Testament's pattern for prayer that responds to revelation. David goes in, *sits* before the LORD (an unusual posture — Eastern monarchs stand to receive; David sits to receive), and begins not with petition but with worshipful astonishment: 'Who am I, O Lord GOD, and what is my house, that You have brought me this far?' (v. 18). The prayer's logic moves: I am unworthy (vv. 18-20) → You have done this for Your own word's sake (v. 21) → therefore You are uniquely great (v. 22) → and Israel is uniquely Your people (vv. 23-24) → therefore do what You have said (vv. 25-29). David prays God's promise back to God. The whole movement is the inverse of the chapter's opening: David began by proposing what he would do for God; he ends by asking God to do what God has already promised. That reversal is the chapter's discipleship lesson."
